<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF110-374-520  </DOCNO><DOCID>10 374 520.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>ACM Transactions on Database Systems  Dec 1990 v15 n4 p483(35).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Concepts and effectiveness of the cover-coefficient-basedclustering methodology for text databases. (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Can, Fazli; Ozkarahan, Esen A.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>An information retrieval system (IRS) is different from a database management system (DBMS).andP;  An IRS uses a similarity measureto determine relevance; a DBMS returns facts that satisfy aBoolean qualification evaluation.andP;  Clustering in IRS means thathomogeneous groups of documents are associated more strongly witheach other than with those in other groups so clustering documentsin a data base increases IRS efficiency and effectiveness becauseof the hypothesis that states 'closely associated documents tendto be relevant to the same request.' The cover coefficient conceptis a way to estimate the number of clusters in a document database; it also relates indexing and clustering analytically.andO;Cluster-based retrieval aids browsing and provides easy access tocomplete document information.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Data Base Management SystemsInformation Storage and RetrievalAlgorithmsText Data BasesClusteringCluster AnalysisMethodsData Base DesignTheoretical Research.andO;Feature:   illustrationcharttable.andO;Caption:   Example D matrix. (chart)C matrix corresponding to the example D matrix. (chart)Properties of the C matrix. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>